 "response_text": "At initialization, no households have engaged in social learning. The number of households utilizing social learning increases monotonically from this starting point, exhibiting rapid early growth that progressively decelerates until stabilizing approximately two-thirds through the 100-year simulation period.\n\nDuring the initial decade, adoption occurs at a rate of roughly 1.43 households per year, with an early inflection point at year 7 signaling the transition from initial acceleration to sustained expansion. From years 11 to 21, growth continues at 1.14 households per year. A marked deceleration begins around year 22, with the rate dropping to 0.18 households per year through year 43, accompanied by successive inflection points at years 28, 30, 33, and 38 that indicate stepwise adjustments in the adoption trajectory. Following a detected change point at year 40, the expansion slows dramatically to 0.029 households per year through year 54, and further diminishes to 0.008 households per year through year 65.\n\nThe system approaches a plateau near year 63, reaching a maximum mean value of 32.07 households (approximately 53% of the 60 households) engaged in social learning. This level persists through year 100 with a terminal value of 32.07. The overall temporal mean stands at 27.43 households, with a median of 31.90, reflecting that for the majority of the simulation duration, adoption remains near the upper asymptote.\n\nOscillatory dynamics are superimposed on this growth pattern, particularly evident around years 22–32 and 51–59, suggesting periodic fluctuations in adoption rates. Across the 30 stochastic realizations, final outcomes vary substantially, ranging from approximately 18 to 54 households, indicating that social learning penetration spans from roughly 30% to 90% of the farming population depending on stochastic environmental and social factors.\n\nIn the context of the grazing system, this pattern reflects the diffusion of social learning strategies among smallholder farmers managing private pastures under variable rainfall conditions. The initial absence of social learning suggests that farmers begin with their assigned baseline or experiential strategies, then progressively adopt social observation as they gather information about neighbors' outcomes. The eventual saturation below universal adoption indicates that a significant subset of farmers—averaging 28 households but ranging from 6 to 42 depending on the stochastic realization—maintains non-social learning approaches throughout the simulation period. The oscillations in adoption rates likely correspond to the high annual rainfall variability (standard deviation of 100 units around a mean of 200), which creates episodic conditions prompting reassessment of stocking decisions and triggering waves of social learning adoption."

